INTRODUCTION
The holiday season is a time of joy, togetherness, and celebration. For many, it’s a season to reconnect with loved ones, enjoy festive traditions, and reflect on the year gone by.
However, sometimes we put so much focus and energy into plans and others that we forget to take care of ourselves. The to-do list tends to get longer around the holidays and the hustle gets real… We want to deliver and do it all! Healthy habits can easily get lost.
Remember this: Everything has a ripple effect.
The better you feel, the better you move. You need energy to tackle that to-do list! So taking the time to care for yourself, even in the busiest of times, isn’t selfish at all. It’s an investment in everything and everyone you love around you.
We care deeply about your well-being. This holiday season, we encourage you to find joy in the moments, cherish your health, and take steps to care for your body and mind. By prioritizing your wellness, you ensure that you’ll enter the new year ready to embrace all it has to offer.

Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
Self Care
Prioritize sleep: Not getting enough sleep can lead to decreased energy levels, brain fog, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, mood swings, and slower reaction times. Aim for 7-9 hours of sleep to support your immune system and energy levels.
Schedule downtime: Build in "me time" for activities like taking a walk, reading, meditating, etc. Write it down too! Make it part of your plan.
Practice mindfulness: Engage in deep breathing, meditation, or stretching to manage stress and improve focus.
Hydrate: Drinking enough water is crucial for maintaining overall health and proper bodily functions. Water plays a vital role in regulating body temperature, lubricating joints, transporting nutrients, protecting organs, increasing calorie burning, and is necessary to burn fat. Dehydration can significantly impact energy levels, causing fatigue and lethargy. Drink at least 64 oz a day!
4
Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
Stay active:
Don’t skip that workout! It’ll help you be more productive. MOVEMENT = ENERGY!
How Exercise Boosts Energy: Improves oxygen circulation: Exercise increases blood flow and oxygen delivery to muscles, providing them with more energy. Stimulates endorphin release: Exercise triggers the release of endorphins, natural mood boosters that can also increase energy levels. Improves sleep quality: Regular exercise can lead to better sleep, which is essential for feeling refreshed and energized. Increases mitochondrial function: Mitochondria are the energy-producing organelles in cells. Exercise can improve mitochondrial function, leading to more efficient energy production. Reduces stress: Exercise can help reduce stress levels, which can contribute to feelings of fatigue.

Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
Stay on Track during those big Holiday Dinners
1. Don’t skip breakfast! Break your fast and kick start your metabolism. This helps stabilize blood sugar levels, prevent pre-dinner cravings and overeating at dinner. Also, studies show that people who skip meals on holidays end up eating more calories overall than those who eat breakfast & lunch at their regular times.
2. Drink LOTS of water! Especially right before and after your big holiday meal Enhanced Digestive Efficiency Drinking water before meals primes your digestive system for optimal performance. It helps produce adequate stomach acid and digestive enzymes, ensuring proper breakdown of foods. This preparatory hydration also helps prevent digestive issues like constipation and bloating, demonstrating just one of the 100 benefits of drinking water when timed correctly around meals. Weight Management Support One of the most significant benefits of drinking water before meals is its impact on weight management. Studies have shown that pre-meal water consumption can reduce caloric intake by creating a feeling of fullness,

making drinking water to lose weight an effective strategy. This natural appetite suppression can help control portion sizes and support long-term weight management goals.. Improved Nutrient Absorption Proper hydration after meals aids in the efficient transportation of nutrients throughout your body. The importance of water in the body becomes particularly evident during the digestive process, as water helps break down food and facilitates the absorption of nutrients through the intestinal walls, ensuring maximum benefit from your meals. Metabolic Boost Water consumption around meals can increase your metabolic rate, supporting better calorie burning and energy utilization. Toxin Elimination Regular water intake before and after meals helps flush toxins from your system more effectively. 3. Use a smaller plate Going for a second plate is totally understandable on this delicious holiday! Use a smaller plate for portion control. If there are no smaller plates available you can use the inner rim of a bigger plate.
4. Avoid certain parts of a dish Enjoy the turkey, but avoid the skin. Enjoy those mashed sweet potatoes, but scrape off the marshmallow. Enjoy that salad, but remove the croutons.
5. Eat slowly and mindfully - (grazing, smaller plate) In general, it takes 20 minutes for our body to feel full once we’ve started eating. If you eat too fast you may overeat because you aren’t yet aware that you are full. Eating too fast may also cause us to take bites way too big or not chew enough. Chewing your food properly and thoroughly can help in smooth digestion and nutrient absorption. When you don't chew your food enough, the rest of your digestive system becomes confused. Your body may not produce enough of the enzymes needed to fully break down your food. This could lead to digestive problems, like bloating and constipation.
8
Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
One of my favorite hacks, not just for big holiday dinners but eating in general, is putting down the fork every 3 bites… Take a break, look up from your plate & around the table, talk, engage, be in the moment.
6. Prioritize your veggies and protein Make sure you’re getting your necessary nutrients before indulging and getting full on the “bad” stuff. This will also help you eat less unnecessary carbs and sweets. That doesn’t mean you can’t have those treats!
7. Indulge in moderation Holidays come once a year… You don’t have to give up on your favorite dishes completely! It doesn’t have to be 0 or 100. Allowing a treat every now and then is healthy! Constantly denying your desires can later lead to overindulging. Find your balance.
8. Stop eating when you’re full or something is no longer enjoyable. There will probably be leftovers! The whole point of food is to nourish our bodies, not hurt it. Put down that fork if you are no longer hungry. You can always make yourself another small plate later when you’re hungry or tomorrow for lunch!
9
Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
9. Use the extra energy to crush your next workout What fuels energy? FOOD! When glycogen is filled, eating extra calories and carbs can play a role in making you gain weight. However, when it’s depleted, the food you eat will go to refueling your body, restoring your energy, and helping you build muscle and repair after a tough workout.
10. Most importantly, focus on enjoying your time with your loved ones, instead of obsessing over what you are eating. That’s what it’s all about! Enjoy the moments.

HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Healthy Caramel Apple Dip
Makes 4 servings
Ingredients:
10 medjool dates (pitted) 1/2 cup hot water (more if necessary) 1/4 cup almond butter 1/2 tsp. pure vanilla extract 1/4 tsp. ground cinnamon 1-2 apples, sliced (to serve with)
Instructions:
1. Add medjool dates and water to the pitcher of a high-speed blender. If necessary, let sit for 10-30 minutes first, until the dates have softened a bit. 2. Add the almond butter, vanilla, and cinnamon if using. Puree on high speed until completely smooth, a minute or two. Add more water, a tablespoon at a time, if needed to keep things moving. 3. Transfer to a serving bowl. Serve with apple slices. Enjoy! 4. Keeps in an airtight container in the refrigerator for several days

HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Raspberry Chocolate Almond Clusters
Serving size = 1-2 clusters
Ingredients:
1/2 cup Raspberries 1/2 cup Almonds, roughly chopped (measure then chop) 1 cup Cacao Chips (70% or higher cacao)
Instructions:
1.Wash well & lay the raspberries out to dry on a paper towel or dish cloth. 2.When the seeds have dried out a bit, begin melting the chocolate chips over a double boiler, stirring occasionally until all the chips have melted together. (or microwave for 1 min stirring at 30 seconds) 3.While the chocolate chips are melting, roughly chop the almonds. 4.Once the chocolate chips have fully melted and look nice and smooth, remove it from the heat and gently stir in the almonds. 5.Pour little dollops of the mixture onto a parchment lined baking sheet making even little clusters. 6.Place tray with the clusters into the fridge for about an hour while the chocolate sets. 7.Eat and enjoy!

HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Vegan Date Cookies
Serving size = 1-2 cookies
Ingredients:
1 cup pitted Medjool dates 1 cup almond butter ½ tsp baking soda ½-1 tsp Apple cider vinegar 1 tsp vanilla extract 1 TBSP ground flax seeds 1 tsp water
Instructions:
1.Place the dates into the blender & blend 2.Add the rest of the ingredients to the blended dates & blend again 3.Roll out cookie batter into small circular balls 4.Place on a baking sheet 5.Bake in oven at 350 F degrees for 13-15 minutes 6.Take out of the oven and cool 7.Serve + enjoy!

Baked Apple Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
1 Apple 1 Teaspoon Ground Cinnamon 1/2 Teaspoon Ground Nutmeg Coconut Oil
Instructions:
1.Slice the apple in half 2.Place the halves cut side up on a baking dish 3.Sprinkle with cinnamon and nutmeg 4.Drizzle a little coconut oil on top 5.Place in the oven at 350° for 10-15 minutes 6.Bake apples until tender

Holiday Skinny Sangria Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
1 inch slice of fresh ginger, thinly sliced 1 large sprig fresh rosemary A few orange slices 1/2 cup 100% cranberry juice (no added sugar) 1 cup (8 oz) sparkling water / club soda Fresh cranberries for garnish

HEALTHY MOCKTAIL RECIPES
Mint Cucumber Cooler
Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
6 mint leaves 1 tablespoon of honey, agave syrup, or maple syrup A few cucumber slices 1 cup (8 oz) sparkling water Handful ice cubes Jalapeño, sliced (optional spicy)
Instructions:
1.Muddle mint leaves at the bottom of a cocktail shaker/glass using a wooden spoon or muddler. 2.Stir in honey, agave syrup, or maple syrup to incorporate. 3.Add cucumber to the mixture. 4.Add a handful of ice cubes to the glass. 5.Pour sparkling water into drinking glasses, then add in cucumber and mint mixture 6.Top with optional jalapeño slices. Enjoy!

HEALTHY MOCKT AIL RECIPES
Vegan Eggnog
Makes 6 servings
Ingredients:
6 pitted Medjool dates 1 cup (115 g.) raw cashews 2 1/4 cups water, plus more for soaking 1 cup canned full-fat coconut milk 1/4 cup pure maple syrup 1 Tbsp. pure vanilla extract 1 tsp. ground cinnamon 1/4 tsp. grated fresh nutmeg, plus more for serving 1/4 tsp. kosher salt Dairy-free whipped topping, such as Silk dairy-free heavy whipping cream, for serving
Instructions:
1.Place dates and cashews in a resealable container and cover with at least 2" water. Cover and soak for at least 4 hours or up to 12. 2.Drain and rinse dates and cashews. Transfer to a high-powered blender. Add milk, maple syrup, vanilla, cinnamon, nutmeg, salt, and 2 1/4 cups water. Blend until smooth and creamy. 3.Transfer eggnog to a resealable jar or airtight container. Refrigerate until thickened and cold, at least 2 hours and up to 3 days. 4.Serve cold (shake before serving if mixture has separated), dolloped or piped with dairy-free whipping cream and sprinkled with more nutmeg.

Ingredients:

HEALTHY MEAL / SIDE DISH IDEAS
Cauliflower Mashed Potatoes Serving size = 1 cup
Ingredients:
1 medium-sized head of cauliflower, chopped into florets (about 1 1/2-2 lbs.) 1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil 6 garlic cloves , minced Salt and pepper, to taste Cheese of choice (optional)
Instructions:
1.Steam cauliflower for about 5-8 mins Set aside to dry. 2.Add olive oil to pan and cook garlic for about 2 minutes. 3.Put garlic and cauliflower into a food processor with salt and pepper and process until it resembles mashed potatoes. 4.Stir in cheese to make creamier (optional)

Stuffed Sweet Potato Boat Recipe
Makes 2 servings Serving size = 1 stuffed sweet potato
Ingredients:
2 large sweet potatoes 1 cup Brussels sprouts, halved 1 cup butternut squash, cubed 2 tablespoons olive oil Salt and pepper, to taste 1/2 teaspoon garlic powder 1/4 cup dried cranberries 1/4 cup crumbled goat cheese 1 tablespoon maple syrup (optional for extra sweetness) Fresh parsley for garnish (optional)
Instructions:

Ingredients:
10 medjool dates (pitted) 1/2 cup hot water (more if necessary) 1/4 cup almond butter 1/2 tsp. pure vanilla extract 1/4 tsp. ground cinnamon 1-2 apples, sliced (to serve with)
Instructions:
1. Add medjool dates and water to the pitcher of a high-speed blender. If necessary, let sit for 10-30 minutes first, until the dates have softened a bit. 2. Add the almond butter, vanilla, and cinnamon if using. Puree on high speed until completely smooth, a minute or two. Add more water, a tablespoon at a time, if needed to keep things moving. 3. Transfer to a serving bowl. Serve with apple slices. Enjoy! 4. Keeps in an airtight container in the refrigerator for several days

HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Raspberry Chocolate Almond Clusters
Serving size = 1-2 clusters
Ingredients:
1/2 cup Raspberries 1/2 cup Almonds, roughly chopped (measure then chop) 1 cup Cacao Chips (70% or higher cacao)
Instructions:
1.Wash well & lay the raspberries out to dry on a paper towel or dish cloth. 2.When the seeds have dried out a bit, begin melting the chocolate chips over a double boiler, stirring occasionally until all the chips have melted together. (or microwave for 1 min stirring at 30 seconds) 3.While the chocolate chips are melting, roughly chop the almonds. 4.Once the chocolate chips have fully melted and look nice and smooth, remove it from the heat and gently stir in the almonds. 5.Pour little dollops of the mixture onto a parchment lined baking sheet making even little clusters. 6.Place tray with the clusters into the fridge for about an hour while the chocolate sets. 7.Eat and enjoy!
12
HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Vegan Date Cookies
Serving size = 1-2 cookies
Ingredients:
1 cup pitted Medjool dates 1 cup almond butter ½ tsp baking soda ½-1 tsp Apple cider vinegar 1 tsp vanilla extract 1 TBSP ground flax seeds 1 tsp water
Instructions:
1.Place the dates into the blender & blend 2.Add the rest of the ingredients to the blended dates & blend again 3.Roll out cookie batter into small circular balls 4.Place on a baking sheet 5.Bake in oven at 350 F degrees for 13-15 minutes 6.Take out of the oven and cool 7.Serve + enjoy!

HEALTHY TREAT RECIPES
Baked Apple Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
1 Apple 1 Teaspoon Ground Cinnamon 1/2 Teaspoon Ground Nutmeg Coconut Oil
Instructions:
1.Slice the apple in half 2.Place the halves cut side up on a baking dish 3.Sprinkle with cinnamon and nutmeg 4.Drizzle a little coconut oil on top 5.Place in the oven at 350° for 10-15 minutes 6.Bake apples until tender

HEALTHY MOCKTAIL RECIPES
Holiday Skinny Sangria Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
1 inch slice of fresh ginger, thinly sliced 1 large sprig fresh rosemary A few orange slices 1/2 cup 100% cranberry juice (no added sugar) 1 cup (8 oz) sparkling water / club soda Fresh cranberries for garnish
Instructions:
1.Muddle sliced ginger, rosemary, and orange slices together using the end of a wooden spoon or a muddler if you have one. Add cranberry juice and club soda, garnish and enjoy !

HEALTHY MOCKTAIL RECIPES
Mint Cucumber Cooler
Makes 1 serving
Ingredients:
6 mint leaves 1 tablespoon of honey, agave syrup, or maple syrup A few cucumber slices 1 cup (8 oz) sparkling water Handful ice cubes Jalapeño, sliced (optional spicy)
Instructions:
1.Muddle mint leaves at the bottom of a cocktail shaker/glass using a wooden spoon or muddler. 2.Stir in honey, agave syrup, or maple syrup to incorporate. 3.Add cucumber to the mixture. 4.Add a handful of ice cubes to the glass. 5.Pour sparkling water into drinking glasses, then add in cucumber and mint mixture 6.Top with optional jalapeño slices. Enjoy!
16
HEALTHY MOCKT AIL RECIPES
Vegan Eggnog
Makes 6 servings
Ingredients:
6 pitted Medjool dates 1 cup (115 g.) raw cashews 2 1/4 cups water, plus more for soaking 1 cup canned full-fat coconut milk 1/4 cup pure maple syrup 1 Tbsp. pure vanilla extract 1 tsp. ground cinnamon 1/4 tsp. grated fresh nutmeg, plus more for serving 1/4 tsp. kosher salt Dairy-free whipped topping, such as Silk dairy-free heavy whipping cream, for serving
Instructions:
1.Place dates and cashews in a resealable container and cover with at least 2" water. Cover and soak for at least 4 hours or up to 12. 2.Drain and rinse dates and cashews. Transfer to a high-powered blender. Add milk, maple syrup, vanilla, cinnamon, nutmeg, salt, and 2 1/4 cups water. Blend until smooth and creamy. 3.Transfer eggnog to a resealable jar or airtight container. Refrigerate until thickened and cold, at least 2 hours and up to 3 days. 4.Serve cold (shake before serving if mixture has separated), dolloped or piped with dairy-free whipping cream and sprinkled with more nutmeg.

HEALTHY MEAL / SIDE DISH IDEAS
Gut Healthy Garlic Tahini Dressing
Salad dressing, 1 serving = 2 tbsp
Ingredients:
1/4 cup raw tahini 1 tbsp EVOO 2 garlic cloves (or more, to taste) 2 medium dates, pitted 1/2 cup water
Instructions:
1.Add everything to a blender and blend until smooth. Enjoy! * Great as a salad dressing, dipping veggies, and a mix for pasta/potato/egg salads

HEALTHY MEAL / SIDE DISH IDEAS
Vegetarian Cauliflower Stuffing Makes 2-4 servings Serving size = ½ - 1 cup
Ingredients:
4 tbsp avocado or coconut oil 1 onion, chopped 2 large carrots, peeled and chopped 2 celery stalks, chopped or thinly sliced 1 small head cauliflower, chopped 1/4 cup freshly chopped parsley 2 tbsp. freshly chopped rosemary 1 tbsp. freshly chopped sage (or 1 tsp. ground sage) 1/2 cup low-sodium vegetable broth Salt & Pepper to taste
Instructions:
1.Melt Oil in a pan. Add onion, carrot, and celery and sauté until soft, 7-8 minutes. 2.Add cauliflower and season with salt and pepper. Cook until tender, 8-10 minutes more. 3.Add parsley and rosemary, stir until combined. Pour over broth and cook until totally tender and liquid is absorbed for 10 minutes. 4.ENJOY! 19
HEALTHY MEAL / SIDE DISH IDEAS
Cauliflower Mashed Potatoes Serving size = 1 cup
Ingredients:
1 medium-sized head of cauliflower, chopped into florets (about 1 1/2-2 lbs.) 1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil 6 garlic cloves , minced Salt and pepper, to taste Cheese of choice (optional)
Instructions:
1.Steam cauliflower for about 5-8 mins Set aside to dry. 2.Add olive oil to pan and cook garlic for about 2 minutes. 3.Put garlic and cauliflower into a food processor with salt and pepper and process until it resembles mashed potatoes. 4.Stir in cheese to make creamier (optional)

HEALTHY MEAL / SIDE DISH IDEAS
Stuffed Sweet Potato Boat Recipe
Makes 2 servings Serving size = 1 stuffed sweet potato
Ingredients:
2 large sweet potatoes 1 cup Brussels sprouts, halved 1 cup butternut squash, cubed 2 tablespoons olive oil Salt and pepper, to taste 1/2 teaspoon garlic powder 1/4 cup dried cranberries 1/4 cup crumbled goat cheese 1 tablespoon maple syrup (optional for extra sweetness) Fresh parsley for garnish (optional)
Instructions:
1.Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C) and line a baking sheet with parchment paper. 2.Roast the Sweet Potatoes: Wash the sweet potatoes thoroughly, pat them dry, and pierce them several times with a fork. Place the sweet potatoes directly on the oven rack and roast for 45-50 minutes until tender. 3.Roast the Brussels Sprouts and Butternut Squash: While the sweet potatoes are roasting, toss the Brussels sprouts and butternut squash with olive oil, garlic powder, salt, and pepper. Spread them evenly on the prepared baking sheet and roast for 20-25 minutes, stirring halfway through until golden and crispy. 4.Prepare the Sweet Potato Boats: Once the sweet potatoes are tender, remove them from the oven and let them cool slightly. Slice them lengthwise, creating a "boat." Scoop out & set aside a little of the flesh to create space for the filling (use as side dish with the same toppings or simply enjoy with your meal!) 5.Assemble the Stuffed Boats: Fill each sweet potato boat with the roasted Brussels sprouts and butternut squash. Sprinkle the dried cranberries and crumbled goat cheese on top. Drizzle with maple syrup if you like a touch of sweetness. 6.Serve: Garnish with fresh parsley and serve warm for a cozy, fall-inspired dish that’s perfect as a side or main course. 21","Chunks":[{"CellGUID":"a484d681-57ca-4795-84aa-610747201cd2","Text":"HHOOLLIIDDAAYY WWEELLLLNNEESSSS GGUUIIDDEE

INTRODUCTION
The holiday season is a time of joy, togetherness, and celebration. For many, it’s a season to reconnect with loved ones, enjoy festive traditions, and reflect on the year gone by.
However, sometimes we put so much focus and energy into plans and others that we forget to take care of ourselves. The to-do list tends to get longer around the holidays and the hustle gets real… We want to deliver and do it all! Healthy habits can easily get lost.
Remember this: Everything has a ripple effect.
The better you feel, the better you move. You need energy to tackle that to-do list! So taking the time to care for yourself, even in the busiest of times, isn’t selfish at all. INTRODUCTION
The holiday season is a time of joy, togetherness, and celebration. For many, it’s a season to reconnect with loved ones, enjoy festive traditions, and reflect on the year gone by.
However, sometimes we put so much focus and energy into plans and others that we forget to take care of ourselves. The to-do list tends to get longer around the holidays and the hustle gets real… We want to deliver and do it all! Healthy habits can easily get lost.
Remember this: Everything has a ripple effect.
The better you feel, the better you move. You need energy to tackle that to-do list! So taking the time to care for yourself, even in the busiest of times, isn’t selfish at all. It","’s an investment in everything and everyone you love around you.
We care deeply about your well-being. This holiday season, we encourage you to find joy in the moments, cherish your health, and take steps to care for your body and mind. By prioritizing your wellness, you ensure that you’ll enter the new year ready to embrace all it has to offer.

Manage Stress - Planning is KEY!
Take a moment to look at the week ahead, organize your thoughts and goals.
Plan ahead: Create a realistic schedule that balances holiday activities with your usual routine and self-care needs. Create lists, set priorities, and don't hesitate to ask for help. Don't overschedule yourself, and be prepared to adjust as needed.
WRITE EVERYTHING DOWN. 1. Enhances clarity and focus 2. Boosts motivation and commitment 3. Improves planning and organization"," 4. Increases accountability 5. Facilitates tracking and evaluation
Prioritize tasks and activities: Decide what's truly important and don't be afraid to say "no" to things that will drain you.
Delegate when possible: Share responsibilities with loved ones to ease the burden of holiday preparations.

Create a budget and stick to it: This can significantly reduce financial stress.
Plan your meals and snacks: This helps you stay on track by eliminating the stress and indecision of daily meal decisions. Or just follow a Svelte meal plan! Everything is already done and laid out for you.
Set realistic expectations: It's okay to let go of perfection and focus on enjoying the moment.
Acknowledge your feelings: It's normal to feel a range of emotions during the holidays, including grief or sadness.
Communicate boundaries: Be clear about your needs and limits to avoid over","extending yourself.
Practice gratitude: Reflect on what you're thankful for to shift your focus towards the positive aspects of the season.

Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
Self Care
Prioritize sleep: Not getting enough sleep can lead to decreased energy levels, brain fog, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, mood swings, and slower reaction times. Aim for 7-9 hours of sleep to support your immune system and energy levels.
Schedule downtime: Build in "me time" for activities like taking a walk, reading, meditating, etc. Write it down too! Make it part of your plan.
Practice mindfulness: Engage in deep breathing, meditation, or stretching to manage stress and improve focus.
Hydrate: Drinking enough water is crucial for maintaining overall health and proper bodily functions. Water plays a vital role in regulating body temperature, lubricating joints, transporting nutrients, protecting organs, increasing calorie burning, and is necessary"," to burn fat. Dehydration can significantly impact energy levels, causing fatigue and lethargy. Drink at least 64 oz a day!

Stay active:
Don’t skip that workout! It’ll help you be more productive. MOVEMENT = ENERGY!
How Exercise Boosts Energy: Improves oxygen circulation: Exercise increases blood flow and oxygen delivery to muscles, providing them with more energy. Stimulates endorphin release: Exercise triggers the release of endorphins, natural mood boosters that can also increase energy levels. Improves sleep quality: Regular exercise can lead to better sleep, which is essential for feeling refreshed and energized. Increases mitochondrial function: Mitochondria are the energy-producing organelles in cells. Exercise can improve mitochondrial function, leading to more efficient energy production. Reduces stress: Exercise can help reduce stress levels, which can contribute to feelings of fatigue.

Stay on Track during those big Holiday Dinners
1. Don’t skip breakfast! Break your fast and kick start your metabolism. This helps stabilize blood sugar levels, prevent pre-dinner cravings and overeating at dinner. Also, studies show that people who skip meals on holidays end up eating more calories overall than those who eat breakfast & lunch at their regular times.
2. Drink LOTS of water! Especially right before and after your big holiday meal Enhanced Digestive Efficiency Drinking water before meals primes your digestive system for optimal performance. It helps produce adequate stomach acid and digestive enzymes, ensuring proper breakdown of foods. This preparatory hydration also helps prevent digestive issues like constipation and bloating, demonstrating just one of the 100 benefits of drinking water when timed correctly around meals. Weight Management Support One of the most significant benefits of drinking water before meals is its impact on weight management. Studies have shown that"," pre-meal water consumption can reduce caloric intake by creating a feeling of fullness,

making drinking water to lose weight an effective strategy. This natural appetite suppression can help control portion sizes and support long-term weight management goals.. Improved Nutrient Absorption Proper hydration after meals aids in the efficient transportation of nutrients throughout your body. The importance of water in the body becomes particularly evident during the digestive process, as water helps break down food and facilitates the absorption of nutrients through the intestinal walls, ensuring maximum benefit from your meals. Metabolic Boost Water consumption around meals can increase your metabolic rate, supporting better calorie burning and energy utilization. This metabolic enhancement is one of the key health benefits of drinking water, as it helps maintain a healthy weight while ensuring optimal body function and energy levels throughout the day. Toxin Elimination Regular water intake before and after meals helps flush toxins from your system more effectively."," This cleansing effect supports kidney function and helps maintain a healthy digestive tract, demonstrating why the benefits of drinking more water extend beyond simple hydration to overall body cleansing and maintenance.

Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
3. Use a smaller plate Going for a second plate is totally understandable on this delicious holiday! Use a smaller plate for portion control. If there are no smaller plates available you can use the inner rim of a bigger plate.
4. Avoid certain parts of a dish Enjoy the turkey, but avoid the skin. Enjoy those mashed sweet potatoes, but scrape off the marshmallow. Enjoy that salad, but remove the croutons.
5. Eat slowly and mindfully - (grazing, smaller plate) In general, it takes 20 minutes for our body to feel full once we’ve started eating. If you eat too fast you may overeat because you aren’t yet aware that you are full. Eating too fast may"," also cause us to take bites way too big or not chew enough. Chewing your food properly and thoroughly can help in smooth digestion and nutrient absorption. When you don't chew your food enough, the rest of your digestive system becomes confused. Your body may not produce enough of the enzymes needed to fully break down your food. This could lead to digestive problems, like bloating and constipation.
8
Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
One of my favorite hacks, not just for big holiday dinners but eating in general, is putting down the fork every 3 bites… Take a break, look up from your plate & around the table, talk, engage, be in the moment.
6. Prioritize your veggies and protein Make sure you’re getting your necessary nutrients before indulging and getting full on the “bad” stuff. This will also help you eat less unnecessary carbs and sweets. That doesn’t mean you can’t have"," those treats!
7. Indulge in moderation Holidays come once a year… You don’t have to give up on your favorite dishes completely! It doesn’t have to be 0 or 100. Allowing a treat every now and then is healthy! Constantly denying your desires can later lead to overindulging. Find your balance.
8. Stop eating when you’re full or something is no longer enjoyable. There will probably be leftovers! The whole point of food is to nourish our bodies, not hurt it. Put down that fork if you are no longer hungry. You can always make yourself another small plate later when you’re hungry or tomorrow for lunch!
9
Self Care Tips and Tricks - Staying Healthy during Holidays
9. Use the extra energy to crush your next workout What fuels energy? FOOD! When glycogen is filled, eating extra calories and carbs can play a role in making you gain weight. However, when it","’s depleted, the food you eat will go to refueling your body, restoring your energy, and helping you build muscle and repair after a tough workout.
10. Most importantly, focus on enjoying your time with your loved ones, instead of obsessing over what you are eating. That’s what it’s all about! Enjoy the moments.

Healthy Caramel Apple Dip
Makes 4 servings
Ingredients:

Instructions:
1. Add medjool dates and water to the pitcher of a high-speed blender. If necessary, let sit for 10-30 minutes first, until the dates have softened a bit. 2",". Transfer to a serving bowl. Serve with apple slices. Enjoy! 4. Keeps in an airtight container in the refrigerator for several days

Ingredients:

Instructions:

Vegan Eggnog
Makes 6 servings
Ingredients:
6 pitted Medjool dates 1 cup (115 g.) raw cashews 2 1/4 cups water, plus more for soaking 1 cup canned full-fat coconut milk 1/4 cup pure maple syrup 1 Tbsp. pure vanilla extract 1 tsp. ground cinnamon 1/4 tsp. grated fresh nutmeg, plus more for serving 1/4 tsp. kosher salt Dairy-free whipped topping, such as Silk dairy-free heavy whipping cream, for serving","
Instructions:
1.Place dates and cashews in a resealable container and cover with at least 2" water. Cover and soak for at least 4 hours or up to 12. 2.Drain and rinse dates and cashews. Transfer to a high-powered blender. Add milk, maple syrup, vanilla, cinnamon, nutmeg, salt, and 2 1/4 cups water. Blend until smooth and creamy. 3.Transfer eggnog to a resealable jar or airtight container. Refrigerate until thickened and cold, at least 2 hours and up to 3 days. 4.Serve cold (shake before serving if mixture has separated), dolloped or piped with dairy-free whipping cream and sprinkled with more nutmeg.

Makes 2 servings Serving size = 1 stuffed sweet potato
Ingredients:
2 large sweet potatoes 1 cup Brussels sprouts, halved 1 cup butternut squash, cubed 2 tablespoons olive oil Salt and pepper, to taste 1/2 teaspoon garlic powder 1/4 cup dried cranberries 1/4 cup crumbled goat cheese 1 tablespoon maple syrup (optional for extra sweetness) Fresh parsley for garnish (optional)
Instructions:
1.Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C) and line a baking sheet with parchment"," paper. 2.Roast the Sweet Potatoes: Wash the sweet potatoes thoroughly, pat them dry, and pierce them several times with a fork.
